.TH JRNL 1 "2025-03-15" "jrnl 3.0.0" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
jrnl \- minimal CLI journaling tool

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B jrnl
.RI [ operation ] " [entry/specifier]"

.SH DESCRIPTION
jrnl is a small command-line journaling tool that stores
journal entries in a plain-text format and provides simple
filtering based on time and ranges.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR add " " TEXT " " [tag]
Add a new journal entry with an optional tag.

.TP
.BR show " " --before " " TIME
Show entries before TIME.

.TP
.BR show " " --after " " TIME
Show entries after TIME.

.TP
.BR show " " *N
Show the first N entries.

.TP
.BR show " " N*
Show the last N entries.

.TP
.B TIME format
YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM

.TP
.BR backup " " [filename]
Create a backup at the path specified in the configuration
file. An optional filename may be provided.

.TP
.BR -h ", " --help
Show help and exit.

.TP
.BR -v ", " --version
Show version information and exit.

.SH FILES
.TP
.I $XDG_DATA_HOME/jrnl/backup
Default backup directory.

.TP
.I $XDG_DATA_HOME/jrnl/journal.txt
Default journal storage file.

.TP
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/jrnl/config
Configuration file.

.SH NOTES
jrnl is intentionally minimal. Each invocation performs a
single operation, following traditional Unix command-line
tool design. Journal data is stored in plain text and is
safe to inspect or process using standard Unix utilities.

.SH DESIGN
State-changing operations are implemented using atomic
file replacement to avoid partial writes or corrupted
journal states.

.SH EXAMPLES
Add a new entry:
.RS
jrnl add "Finished N-body simulation draft"
.RE

Show the last 3 entries:
.RS
jrnl show 3*
.RE

Create a backup:
.RS
jrnl backup
.RE

